%I A378831 #30 Apr 12 2026 11:03:04
%S A378831 1,2,2,4,5,10,11,21,23,36,35,55,56,78,79,105,97,136,137,171,172,210,
%T A378831 207,253,255
%N A378831 Draw a regular n-gon and join every pair of boundary vertices by a chord, producing a planar graph with A007569(n) nodes; a(n) is the minimum number of chords needed to cover all A007569(n) nodes.
%C A378831 Note that a(n) is not always the same as the minimum number of lines needed if arbitrary lines are permitted. The first known occurrence where the numbers differ is for a(7) = 10 where one can use eight diagonal lines plus one off-diagonal line to cover two vertices so that all vertices can be covered with only 9 lines.
%H A378831 Scott R. Shannon, <a href="/A378831/a378831.png">Image showing one example of 11 diagonals covering all 57 vertices of the octagon</a>. The covering diagonals are shown as thicker white lines.
%Y A378831 Cf. A007569, A373813, A373811.
